{{for|the nuclear power plant in Michigan, USA|Enrico Fermi Nuclear Generating Station}} {{Infobox power station | name = Enrico Fermi Nuclear Power Plant | image = CentraleNucleareEnricoFermi.jpg | image_caption = | location_map = Italy | status = B | operator = | coordinates = {{coord|45|11|02.74|N|8|16|39.20|E|region:IT_type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | np_reactor_type = PWR | ps_units_decommissioned= 1 × 260&nbsp;MW | ps_electrical_capacity = 260 | commissioned = 1964 | decommissioned = 1990 }}
'''Enrico Fermi Nuclear Power Plant''' was a [[nuclear power plant]] at [[Trino]] (often referred to as ‘Trino Vercellese’, meaning ‘Trino in the [[Province of Vercelli]]’), in north-west [[Italy]].
Consisting of one 260 [[megawatt]] [[pressurized water reactor]] (PWR) from the vendor [[Westinghouse Electric Corporation]], it operated from 1964 until 1990. Trino was in 1964 the third ever commercially operated PWR worldwide, and it had the second highest megawatt-capacity of them. It was closed down following the [[Italian nuclear power referendum, 1987]].
The experimental [[Uranium enrichment|enrichment plant]], [[EUREX]], near the power plant, was closed down in 1984.
