den Barnett|title=Charles Wood, the visionary who created Mobile Japanese Garden|url=http://lagniappemobile.com/charles-wood-visionary-created-mobile-japanese-garden/|publisher=Lagniappe Weekly|accessdate=17 July 2016|date=July 22, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=0 Mobile's Japanese Garden to be named in honor of Charles Wood|url=http://blog.al.com/pr-community-news/2010/07/mobiles_japanese_garden_to_be_named_in_honor_of_charles_wood.html|publisher=Alabama Media Group|accessdate=17 July 2016|date=July 3, 2010}}</ref> |- | [[Cheekwood Botanical Garden and Museum of Art]] || [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]] || Tennessee || 55-acre botanical garden includes the Shomu-en, the pine-mist garden |- | [[Chicago Botanic Garden]] || [[Glencoe, Illinois|Glencoe]] || Illinois || Includes the Elizabeth Hubert Malott Japanese Garden, a 17-acre lakeside garden with three islands, also a collection of nearly 200 bonsai |- | [[Cleveland Botanical Garden]] || [[Cleveland, Ohio|Cleveland]] || Ohio || Includes a Japanese garden designed by David Slawson, was a gift of Ikebana International, Chapter 20, in 1975<ref>{{cite web|title=Japanese Garden|url=http://www.cbgarden.org/come-visit/collection-gardens/japanese-garden.aspx|publisher=Cleveland Botanical Garden|accessdate=16 July 2016}}</ref> |- | [[Como Park Zoo and Conservatory]] || [[Saint Paul, Minnesota|Saint Paul]] || Minnesota || The Marjorie McNeely Conservatory includes the Charlotte Partridge Ordway Japanese Garden and a bonsai collection |- | Culver City Julian Dixon Library Kaizuka Meditation Garden || [[Culver City, California|Culver City]] || California || [http://www.colapublib.org/apahm/japanese_gardens.html Website] |- | [[Dawes Arboretum]] || [[Newark, Ohio|Newark]] || Ohio || The Japanese Garden features a meditation house, pond and rock garden and was designed in 1963 by Dr. Makoto Nakamura.<ref>{{cite web|title=Garden Gateway|url=http://dawesarb.org/explore/garden-gateway/|publisher=Dawes Arboretum|accessdate=16