ose]] || California || 5.5 acres, located in [[Kelley Park]], includes three koi ponds, patterned after Japan's famous [[Korakuen Garden]] in [[Okayama]] |- | [[Japanese Garden (Micke Grove Regional Park)|Japanese Garden]] || [[Lodi, California|Lodi]] || California || 3 acres, located in [[Micke Grove Regional Park]], designed by [[Nagao Sakurai]] |- | [[The Japanese Garden]] || Los Angeles || California || Located in [[Van Nuys, Los Angeles|Van Nuys]], {{convert|6.5|acres}} public [[Japanese garden]] located on the grounds of the [[Tillman Water Reclamation Plant]] in the [[Sepulveda Dam|Sepulveda Basin Recreation Area]] of the central [[San Fernando Valley]], designed by Dr. [[Koichi Kawana]] and created from 1980 to 1983 |- | Japanese Tea Garden at Central Park || [[San Mateo, California|San Mateo]] || California || [https://www.cityofsanmateo.org/3319/Central-Park-Japanese-Garden Website], designed by [[Nagao Sakurai]], features a granite pagoda, tea house, koi pond and bamboo grove |- | [[Japanese Tea Garden (San Francisco, California)|Japanese Tea Garden at Golden Gate Park]] || [[San Francisco]] || California || 3 acres, oldest public Japanese garden in the United States, designed by [[Makoto Hagiwara]], includes ponds, a pagoda, moon bridge and a teahouse |- | Japanese-American Cultural and Community Center || Los Angeles || California || [http://www.jaccc.org/jamesirvinejapanesegarden/ Website], includes the James Irvine Japanese Garden, also known as Seiryu-en or "Garden of the Clear Stream", designed by [[Takeo Uesugi]] & Associates<ref>{{cite web|title=Official site|url=http://www.tuainc.com/|publisher=Takeo Uesugi and Associates|accessdate=17 July 2016}}</ref> |- | [[JC Raulston Arboretum]] || [[Raleigh, North Carolina|Raleigh]] || North Carolina || Administered by [[North Carolina State University]], includes a Zen garden of raked gravel and hand-crafted wooden and stone features |- | [[Jo Ryo En Japanese Garden]] at [[Carleton College]] || [[Northfield, Minnesota|Northfield]] || Minnesota || Located behind Watson Hall, opened in 1976<ref>{{cite web|title=Carleton’s Japanese Garden|url=http://apps.carleton.edu/campus/japanesegarden/|publisher=Carleton College|accessdate=16 July 2016}}</ref> |- | [[John P. Humes Japanese Stroll Garden]] || [[Mill Neck, New York|Mill Neck]] || New York || 4 acres, includes a tea house in the shoin-dzukuri style of the Ashikaga period, tea garden, stone lanterns, mosses, waterfall, pond; may be closed |- | [[Kubota Garden]] || [[Seattle]] || Washington || 20 acres with 4.5-acre landscaped core, started in 1927 by [[Fujitaro Kubota]] |- | [[Kyoto Gardens of Honolulu Memorial Park]] || Honolulu || Hawaii || Cemetery with three-tiered Sanju Pagoda, Kinkaku-ji Temple, and Mirror Gardens |- | Lakeside Park || [[Oakland, California|Oakland]] || California || [http://gardensatlakemerritt.org/ Website], includes a Japanese garden, bonsai garden and [[Torii]] gate garden at the Gardens at Lake Merritt |- | [[Lauritzen Gardens]] || [[Omaha, Nebraska|Omaha]] || Nebraska || Planned Japanese garden |- | [[Lendonwood Gardens]] || [[Grove, Oklahoma|Grove]] || Oklahoma || Includes the Japanese Pavilion Garden with a koi pond |- | [[Lewis Ginter Botanical Garden]] || [[Richmond, Virginia|Richmond]] || Virginia || Includes the Asian Valley |- | [[Liliuokalani Park and Gardens]] || [[Hilo]] || Hawaii || 30 acres, Edo-style Japanese gardens with bridges, koi ponds, pagodas, statues, torii, and a Japanese teahouse |- | [[Lithia Park]] || [[Ashland, Oregon|Ashland]] || Oregon || Includes a Japanese garden |- | [[Manito Park and Botanical Gardens]] || [[Spokane, Washington|Spokane]] || Washington || Includes the Nishinomiya Tsutakawa Japanese Garden designed in 1967 by Nagao Sakurai |- | [[Massee Lane Gardens]] || [[Fort Valley, Georgia|Fort Valley]] || Georgia || Includes the Abendroth Japanese Garden with a tea house and koi |- | [[Maymont|Maymont Japanese Garden]] || Richmond || Virginia || Features a 